Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds eight, given that each drug has a success probability of 0.7 and there are 10 independent triples (so each drug is used 10 times).

The number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution: \( S_i \sim \text{Binomial}(n=10, p=0.7) \) for \( i = 1, 2, 3 \), and the \( S_i \) are independent.

The probability that the maximum exceeds eight is \( P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8) \). This is equivalent to \( 1 - P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8) \).

Due to independence, \( P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8) = [P(S_i \leq 8)]^3 \).

For \( S_i \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7) \):
- \( P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_i = 9) - P(S_i = 10) \)
- \( P(S_i = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249 \)
- \( P(S_i = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821 \)
- \( P(S_i > 8) = P(S_i = 9) + P(S_i = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459 \)
- \( P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541 \)

Then:
- \( [P(S_i \leq 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3 \)
- \( (0.8506916541)^2 = 0.723676290385 \)
- \( 0.723676290385 \times 0.8506916541 = 0.6156253775 \)

Thus:
- \( P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8) = 0.6156253775 \)
- \( P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8) = 1 - 0.6156253775 = 0.3843746225 \)

Rounded to three decimal places for reasonable significant figures, the probability is 0.384.

