Problem: 5.5-9. Suppose that the length of life in hours (say, $X$ ) of a light bulb manufactured by company $A$ is $N(800,14400)$ and the length of life in hours (say, $Y$ ) of a light bulb manufactured by company $B$ is $N(850,2500)$. One bulb is randomly selected from each company and is burned until "death."
(a) Find the probability that the length of life of the bulb from company $A$ exceeds the length of life of the bulb from company $B$ by at least 15 hours.
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The life of a bulb from company A is normally distributed with mean 800 hours and variance 14400, so standard deviation 120 hours. The life of a bulb from company B is normally distributed with mean 850 hours and variance 2500, so standard deviation 50 hours. The bulbs are independent.

The difference in life, \(D = X - Y\), is normally distributed with mean \(\mu_D = 800 - 850 = -50\) hours and variance \(\sigma_D^2 = 14400 + 2500 = 16900\), so standard deviation \(\sigma_D = \sqrt{16900} = 130\) hours.

The probability that the life of the bulb from company A exceeds that from company B by at least 15 hours is \(P(D > 15)\). Standardizing, \(P\left( \frac{D - (-50)}{130} > \frac{15 - (-50)}{130} \right) = P(Z > 0.5)\), where \(Z\) is a standard normal variable.

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z > 0.5) = 1 - P(Z < 0.5)\). The cumulative probability \(P(Z < 0.5) \approx 0.6915\), so \(P(Z > 0.5) \approx 1 - 0.6915 = 0.3085\).

The probability is 0.3085, rounded to four decimal places.

