Problem: The ${ }^7 \mathrm{Li}^1 \mathrm{H}$ ground electronic state has $D_0=2.4287 \mathrm{eV}, \nu_e / c=1405.65 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, and $\nu_e x_e / c=23.20 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, where $c$ is the speed of light. (These last two quantities are usually designated $\omega_e$ and $\omega_e x_e$ in the literature.) Calculate $D_e$ for ${ }^7 \mathrm{Li}^1 \mathrm{H}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{eV}$.
Solution: The dissociation energy from the bottom of the potential well, \( D_e \), is calculated using the relationship \( D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE} \), where ZPE is the zero-point energy. The zero-point energy is given by \( \text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} h \nu_e - \frac{1}{4} h \nu_e x_e \), with \( \nu_e / c = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1} \) and \( \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1} \).

First, compute the ZPE in wavenumber units:
\[
\text{ZPE}_{\text{wavenumber}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 - \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025  \text{cm}^{-1}.
\]

Convert this ZPE to eV using the conversion factor \( 1  \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984 \times 10^{-4}  \text{eV} \):
\[
\text{ZPE} = 697.025 \times 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} = 0.0864199476  \text{eV}.
\]

Now, add this to \( D_0 = 2.4287  \text{eV} \):
\[
D_e = 2.4287 + 0.0864199476 = 2.5151199476  \text{eV}.
\]

Rounding to five significant figures (based on the input precision, especially \( D_0 \) with five significant figures) gives \( 2.5151  \text{eV} \).

